<!-- 04 GAS vs ELECTRIC -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Gas &amp; Electric Dryers</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">We repair both — and know where they differ</h2>
    <p class="lead">Gas and electric dryers share many components but fail differently. Our technicians diagnose correctly the first time because they know the difference.</p>

    <div class="grid-2col">
      <div class="type-card-large">
        <div class="type-badge">Electric Dryer</div>
        <h3>Electric Dryer Repair</h3>
        <p>Electric dryers heat with a coiled heating element powered directly from a 240V circuit. When something goes wrong with heating, it's almost always one of a small set of components.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Heating element</strong> — burns out over time, no heat at all</li>
          <li><strong>Thermal fuse</strong> — trips when dryer overheats, usually from blocked vent</li>
          <li><strong>High-limit thermostat</strong> — cuts heat before it reaches dangerous temperatures</li>
          <li><strong>Cycling thermostat</strong> — regulates operating temperature</li>
          <li><strong>Drum belt, idler pulley, drum rollers</strong> — mechanical failures causing noise or stopped drum</li>
          <li><strong>Door switch</strong> — machine won't run with door open, fails over time</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card-large">
        <div class="type-badge">Gas Dryer</div>
        <h3>Gas Dryer Repair</h3>
        <p>Gas dryers use a burner ignited by an igniter and controlled by gas valve coils and a flame sensor. The mechanical components are identical to electric dryers — the heat source is different.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Igniter</strong> — glows to ignite the gas, fails gradually (dryer starts then goes cold)</li>
          <li><strong>Gas valve coils (solenoids)</strong> — hold the valve open during drying cycle</li>
          <li><strong>Flame sensor (radiant sensor)</strong> — detects igniter heat to open gas valve</li>
          <li><strong>Thermal fuse</strong> — same safety role as in electric models</li>
          <li><strong>Drum belt, idler pulley, drum rollers</strong> — identical to electric failures</li>
          <li><strong>Door switch</strong> — identical to electric failure mode</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 DRYER VENT SPOTLIGHT -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Dryer Vent &amp; Fire Safety</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The part of dryer repair most companies skip</h2>
    <p class="lead">We include a vent inspection on every dryer call because the vent is frequently the cause — and always a safety concern in LA's housing stock.</p>

    <div class="vent-block">
      <div class="vent-title">🔥 Dryer Vent Service</div>
      <h3>Why the vent matters more in LA than most cities</h3>
      <p>Most homes and apartments in Los Angeles have a dryer vent that exits through an interior wall, a closet ceiling, or a short exterior run. In the dense housing stock of neighborhoods like West Hollywood, Silver Lake, and Culver City, it's common to find dryers venting through flexible aluminum duct that's been kinked, compressed, or partially disconnected behind the machine. Lint builds up where airflow slows. Heat concentrates where air can't escape.</p>
      <p>A properly functioning dryer vent should push hot, moist air out of the drum and out of the building in a straight, unobstructed run. When it can't do that — due to lint buildup, a crushed flex duct, or a vent cap clogged with debris — the dryer compensates by running longer and hotter. The thermal fuse trips. Clothes don't dry. And in the worst cases, the lint ignites.</p>

      <div class="vent-signs">
        <div class="vent-sign">
          <strong>Clothes take 2+ cycles</strong>
          Restricted airflow — vent is partially blocked
        </div>
        <div class="vent-sign">
          <strong>Dryer gets very hot outside</strong>
          Heat has nowhere to go — vent is blocked
        </div>
        <div class="vent-sign">
          <strong>Thermal fuse keeps blowing</strong>
          Never a coincidence — always a vent issue
        </div>
        <div class="vent-sign">
          <strong>Musty smell from laundry</strong>
          Moisture not exhausting properly
        </div>
        <div class="vent-sign">
          <strong>Vent flap doesn't open</strong>
          Clogged exterior vent cap — complete blockage
        </div>
        <div class="vent-sign">
          <strong>Last vent cleaning: never</strong>
          Annual cleaning is the standard recommendation
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Common Dryer Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>No Heat (Electric)</h3>
        <p>Heating element failure or blown thermal fuse. The thermal fuse is a one-time safety device — once it trips, the dryer won't heat until it's replaced. But replacing just the fuse without finding what caused it to blow (usually a clogged vent) means it blows again in weeks. We fix the fuse and the cause.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>No Heat (Gas)</h3>
        <p>On a gas dryer that starts but goes cold after a few minutes, the igniter or gas valve coils are the most likely culprit. The igniter glows hot enough to open the gas valve — when it weakens, the valve never opens and the heat stops. Technicians often misdiagnose this as a thermal fuse. We test both.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Start</h3>
        <p>Door switch failure is the most common cause — the dryer won't run unless it confirms the door is fully closed. A failed start switch, blown thermal fuse, or in some cases a faulty drive motor can also prevent starting. We carry door switches and start switches for the major brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Drum Not Turning</h3>
        <p>The drum belt is a long, flat belt that wraps around the drum and is driven by the motor through an idler pulley. When it snaps, the motor runs but the drum sits still. This is one of the most satisfying repairs — usually about 45 minutes and the machine is back to normal.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Squealing or Grinding Noise</h3>
        <p>A high-pitched squeal during tumbling is almost always the idler pulley — the spring-loaded pulley that keeps tension on the drum belt. Grinding or thumping means worn drum rollers or drum glides. These are common on any dryer that's run for 5+ years.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Overheating</h3>
        <p>A dryer that runs extremely hot — to the point where clothes come out scorching or the cabinet is uncomfortably hot to touch — is a safety issue. Almost always a blocked vent, but can also be a failed cycling thermostat that isn't regulating temperature correctly. Don't ignore this one.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Takes Too Long to Dry</h3>
        <p>Reduced airflow from a clogged vent is the cause in the majority of these calls. Before concluding it's a heater issue, we check the vent — because cleaning the vent resolves the problem and costs significantly less than a heating element replacement on a unit that wasn't actually broken.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Error Codes (Smart Dryers)</h3>
        <p>Modern dryers from Samsung, LG, and Electrolux display error codes that point to specific failure modes. Our technicians are current on the diagnostic codes for the brands we see most in LA — these codes shorten diagnosis time and reduce guesswork significantly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

